# Contributing to {{PROJECT_NAME}}

Thank you for your interest in contributing. This document covers setup, workflow, and standards.

## Development Setup

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone {{REPO_URL}}
cd {{PROJECT_DIR}}

# Install dependencies
{{INSTALL_COMMAND}}

# Run the test suite
{{TEST_COMMAND}}
```

## Branching Strategy

- `main` — production-ready code
- `develop` — integration branch for the next release
- Feature branches: `feature/short-description`
- Bugfix branches: `fix/issue-number-short-description`

## Commit Messages

Follow [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/):

```
<type>(<scope>): <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`

## Pull Request Process

1. Ensure your branch is up to date with the target branch.
2. Add or update tests for any changed functionality.
3. Update relevant documentation (README, docstrings, API specs).
4. Verify all checks pass: linting, type checking, tests.
5. Request review from at least one maintainer.
6. Squash fixup commits before merging if requested.

## Code Style

- Follow the existing formatting in each file.
- Run the formatter before committing: `{{FORMAT_COMMAND}}`.
- Run the linter before committing: `{{LINT_COMMAND}}`.

## Documentation Requirements

- All public functions, classes, and modules must have docstrings.
- Complex logic must include inline comments explaining *why*, not *what*.
- Update `README.md` if user-facing behavior changes.
- Update `openapi.yaml` if API contracts change.

## Reporting Issues

Use the issue templates provided. Include:

- Steps to reproduce
- Expected vs actual behavior
- Environment details (OS, language version, dependency versions)
- Minimal code sample if applicable
